el where many of humanitarian agencies have stayed. â€œOn Sunday we had just five patients, it was really quiet,â€ said Bill Boyes, spokesman for the International Medical Corps (IMC) in Makeni. â€œThen all of a sudden the ambulances started arriving and we had 16 people and it hasnâ€™t stopped since. I think we have about 50 patients with 31 confirmed Ebola cases,â€ he said. It is the busiest the 100-bed centre has been since it opened in December, with confirmed cases spilling out into an empty convalescent ward. Most of the patients are part of the fishermanâ€™s extended family."</p>
